I don't think that's the way you want to look at things. Saying "I might be shit, but shit sells!" doesn't let you grow and conflates success with worth. A better advice is to ignore people who simple say "it's shit" without providing any other feedback. It might just have been that they didn't like the subject matter, or that they were simply having a bad day. You want to look for actually constructive criticism or take note of what people are commenting on (good and bad) to see where you're doing well and where you're not. Maybe your 100+ pages could be cut down to half without losing anything, and while you have good characters and interesting development people just get bored and stop reading before they get to any of that stuff. Aim to grow, not to please

Yeah, but I sometimes feel like there's this idea that you have to hate what you write or it means it isn't good. The reason you find your old writing bad is because you've improved since writing it, which is - of course - a good thing. On top of that a bit of distance, i.e. time, means you're able to read it more as a reader and less as a creator. You're no longer in that state of mind where it made sense to you as you wrote it; instead you're left trying to figure out what the fuck it's supposed to convey. It's a natural part of the creative process and shouldn't be shunned, but neither is it, in itself, the point

Anonymous Thu 16 Jul 2020 22:24:27 No.31527600 Report
Quoted By:
>>31527016
The phrase I use constantly at work is "think through the tool"
I rarely think of what I'm trying to convey as I write. If I'm able to understand the character and how they respond, then the hard part is reading it afterwards and listening to them.
I rarely write dialogue and the rest of the text together. More than once when I go back to write the missing parts I realize they're lying.

That's my process. However you or another writefag does things will be different.
If you're continually hating the result, spend some time each day on base skills.
Treat it like a workout. Build the base to plan for a taller peak.
